{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619560"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:32:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:32:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16564"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16564"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9255"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74979"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9255","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9255"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16564"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60485"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"149"},{"type":"tags","id":"1380"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6222"},{"type":"tags","id":"6344"},{"type":"tags","id":"7106"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21925"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21929"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74979"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of progressive difficulty walking, urinary incontinence, and forgetfulness. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her gait is broad-based and shuffling. Mini-Mental State Examination score is 22/30. A CT scan of the brain shows enlarged ventricles with preserved cortical sulci.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Non-communicating hydrocephalus","Haemorrhagic stroke","Normal pressure hydrocephalus","Subdural haematoma","Bilateral anterior cerebral artery infarction"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic clinical triad of normal pressure hydrocephalus (NPH): gait disturbance, urinary incontinence, and cognitive decline. The CT findings of ventriculomegaly with preserved cortical sulci are characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal pressure hydrocephalus\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-communicating hydrocephalus\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents more acutely with symptoms of raised intracranial pressure including headache, nausea, and vomiting, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ehaemorrhagic stroke\u003C/strong\u003E would show an acute bleed on CT and presents with sudden onset focal neurological deficits rather than this progressive triad of symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esubdural haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E would appear as a crescent-shaped extra-axial collection on CT, often with mass effect. The clinical presentation would be more acute and may include headache and focal neurological signs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBilateral anterior cerebral artery infarction\u003C/strong\u003E could cause gait problems but would show distinct areas of infarction on CT and would have a more sudden onset.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENPH is important to recognise as it is one of the few potentially reversible causes of dementia. The condition is thought to result from impaired CSF resorption. Early diagnosis and treatment with ventriculoperitoneal shunting can lead to significant improvement in symptoms, particularly gait disturbance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Normal pressure hydrocephalus is characterised by the clinical triad of gait disturbance, urinary incontinence, and cognitive decline.","Ventricular enlargement with preserved sulci is characteristic of normal pressure hydrocephalus on CT imaging.","Normal pressure hydrocephalus is potentially reversible with CSF shunting if diagnosed early."],"references":["Oliveira LM, Nitrini R, Rom\u00e1n GC. Normal-pressure hydrocephalus: A critical review. Dement Neuropsychol. 2019 Apr-Jun;13(2):133-143. doi: 10.1590/1980-57642018dn13-020001. Erratum in: Dement Neuropsychol. 2019 Jul-Sep;13(3):361. doi: 10.1590/1980-57642018dn13-030016. PMID: 31285787; PMCID: PMC6601311.","Patel S, Ditamo M, Mangal R, Gould M, Ganti L. Normal Pressure Hydrocephalus. Cureus. 2023 Feb 18;15(2):e35131. doi: 10.7759/cureus.35131. PMID: 36949988; PMCID: PMC10026533.","Shprecher D, Schwalb J, Kurlan R. Normal pressure hydrocephalus: diagnosis and treatment. Curr Neurol Neurosci Rep. 2008 Sep;8(5):371-6. doi: 10.1007/s11910-008-0058-2. PMID: 18713572; PMCID: PMC2674287."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60485"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16564"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60485","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60485"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T13:13:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T14:05:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9255"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74979"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics